'I2C is a bus protocol — multiple devices share the same SCL and SDA lines simultaneously. Each device has a unique 7-bit address, so there is no conflict. Connect all I2C devices to the same bus (e.g., PB6/PB7 for I2C1). Only use I2C2 if you have an address conflict (two devices with the same address) or need more than ~10 devices. Common I2C addresses: MPU6050=0x68/0x69, BMP280=0x76/0x77, SSD1306 OLED=0x3C/0x3D, DS3231 RTC=0x68 (conflicts with MPU6050!), PCF8574=0x20-0x27, INA219=0x40-0x4F, AHT20=0x38, SHT31=0x44/0x45. When two devices share an address (e.g., MPU6050 at 0x68 and DS3231 at 0x68), put one on I2C2 (PB10/PB11) or change the address via the AD0/SDO pin if supported.');
